'''Shizuri Shrine''' (倭文神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|de|Shintō-Schrein|ja|神社|zh|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in Nishikujō-chō 2-chōme of {{ill|Nara (city)|de|Nara (Stadt)|ja|奈良市|zh|奈良市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara (city)|qq=}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|de|Präfektur Nara|ja|奈良県|zh|奈良县|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara Prefecture|qq=}}.

==History==
According to tradition, in {{ill|Jingo-keiun 2|de|Jingo-keiun 2 (German)|ja|神護景雲|zh|Jingo-keiun 2 (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jingo-keiun 2|qq=}} ({{ill|768|de|768 (German)|ja|768年|zh|768 (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/768|qq=}}), when {{ill|Takemikazuchi|de|Takemikazuchi (German)|ja|武甕槌命|zh|Takemikazuchi (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}} was transferred from {{ill|Kashima Jingu|lt=Kashima Jingu|lt=Kashima Shrine|de|Kashima-Schrein|ja|鹿島神宮|zh|鹿島神宮|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashima Shrine|qq=}} to {{ill|Kasuga-taisha|lt=Kasuga-taisha|lt=Kasuga Shrine|de|Kasuga-Schrein|ja|春日大社|zh|春日大社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kasuga Shrine|qq=}}, the accompanying {{ill|Nakatomi Tokikaze|de|Nakatomi Tokikaze (German)|ja|中臣時風|zh|Nakatomi Tokikaze (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatomi Tokikaze|qq=}} and {{ill|Nakatomi Hideyuki|de|Nakatomi Hideyuki (German)|ja|中臣秀行|zh|Nakatomi Hideyuki (Chinese)|lt=Hideyuki|lt_ja=秀行|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakatomi Hideyuki|qq=}} settled in this Tatsuchi area. They enshrined their ancestral deity, {{ill|Takehazuchi|de|Takehazuchi (German)|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|zh|Takehazuchi (Chinese)|lt=Takehazuchi|lt_ja=武羽槌雄神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|qq=}} (the god of weaving), from {{ill|Hitachi Province|de|Provinz Hitachi|ja|常陸国|zh|常陸國|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachi Province|qq=}}.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}<ref name="genchi">On-site information board</ref>{{sfn|Imperial Household 68}} The {{ill|Shizuri clan|de|Shidori-Clan|ja|倭文部|1=Shizuri clan|2=ja|3=倭文氏|4=zh|5=倭文氏|6=de|7=Shizuri Clan|8=fr|9=Clan Shizuri|lt=Shizuri Bemin (vassals of the Shizuri clan)|lt=Shizuri clan|zh|倭文氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuri clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuri clan|qq=}} are said to be their descendants, residing in Tatsuchi-gō and weaving sacred garments.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}<ref name="genchi">On-site information board</ref> Since ancient times, the shrine has been called either “Shizuri no Yashiro” or “Hizuri no Yashiro.”{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}<ref>''Yamato Meisho Zue''</ref>

==Enshrined Deities==
* {{ill|Takehazuchi|de|Takehazuchi (German)|ja|天羽槌雄神|1=Takehazuchi|2=ja|3=天羽槌雄神|4=zh|5=天羽槌雄神|6=fr|7=Takehazuchi|lt=Takehazuchi|zh|Takehazuchi (Chinese)|lt=Takehazuchi|lt_ja=武羽槌雄神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehazuchi|qq=}}
* {{ill|Futsunushi|de|Futsunushi (German)|ja|経津主神|zh|Futsunushi (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futsunushi|qq=}}
* {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|de|Kaiser Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|zh|Emperor Ōjin (Chinese)|lt=Homuda Wake no Mikoto|lt_ja=誉田別命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ōjin|qq=}}

==Shrine Buildings==
===Main Hall===
A three-bay nagare-zukuri structure with a one-bay portico{{sfn|Nara Prefecture History: Architecture|p=912}}. It is said to be a relocated former main sanctuary of the Thirty-Eight Sub-Shrines of {{ill|Kasuga-taisha|lt=Kasuga-taisha|lt=Kasuga Shrine|de|Kasuga-Schrein|ja|春日大社|zh|春日大社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kasuga Shrine|qq=}}.{{sfn|Nara Prefecture History: Architecture|p=912}}

===Subsidiary Shrines===
====Wakamiya Shrine====
Situated to the right of the main hall, enshrining {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|de|Kaiser Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|zh|仁德天皇|lt=Ōsazaki no Mikoto|lt_ja=大鷦鷯命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Nintoku|qq=}}.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}

====Hebizuka Shrine====
Located in the northeastern corner of the grounds, standing somewhat separately.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}} It enshrines {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|de|Susanoo (German)|ja|スサノオ|zh|須佐之男命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, and is also called “Yasaka Shrine.”{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}} The small sanctuary measures about 2 shaku in width by 1 shaku 6 sun in depth, and on a slightly raised area there is a “snake mound.”{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}

==Festivals==
* March: Kinensai (Prayer Festival)<ref name="genchi" />
* October 10: Annual Festival{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}}<ref name="genchi" />
* November: Niinamesai (Harvest Festival)<ref name="genchi" />
* First day of each month: Tsukinamisai (Monthly Festival)<ref name="genchi" />

===Hebi Matsuri (Snake Festival)===
The annual festival is known as the '''Snake Festival''' (Hebi Matsuri).{{sfn|Nara City History|p=493}} A giant snake about five meters long is fashioned from straw, paraded through the streets, and then placed in the shrine grounds.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=494}} Offerings in the shape of snakes are also made, created from taro stalks.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=494}} Children’s {{ill|Sumo|de|Sumō|ja|相撲|zh|相撲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumo|qq=}} matches are performed, and a sumo {{ill|ema (votive picture)|de|Ema (Votivbild)|ja|絵馬|1=Ema (Shinto)|zh|绘马|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ema (votive picture)|13=User:Immanuelle/Ema (Shinto)|qq=}} from {{ill|1890|de|1890 (German)|ja|1890年|zh|1890 (Chinese)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1890|qq=}} ({{ill|Meiji|de|Meiji-Zeit|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|zh|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 23) is displayed in the offering hall.{{sfn|Nara City History|p=494}}

According to a 1915 ({{ill|Taishō 4|de|Taishō 4 (German)|ja|大正|zh|大正|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō 4|qq=}}) shrine survey, the festival at the time was recorded as follows:{{sfn|Nara City History|p=494}}
<br>“During the annual festival, twelve figures are crafted and inserted into the sacred offerings. A large torch (or straw snake) is also made and carried into the shrine precincts. As soon as the offering is completed, the torch is set aflame and burnt entirely. According to legend, in ancient times there was a giant snake that frequently harmed people. The great priest Ri (Li) Gen Daishi pitied the people’s plight, defeated the snake, and made the land safe.”

